Medical Appointment No Shows¶

Why do 20% of patients miss their scheduled appointments?

Data set from Kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/joniarroba/noshowappointments

By Mahmoud Madkour¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Questions
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

A person makes a doctor appointment, receives all the instructions and no-show.

The most important one if the patient show-up or no-show to the appointment.

The main question we are trying to answer here is why 30% of patients miss their scheduled appointment.

We are trying to predict the most important factors that affect the attendance of the patient.

The dataset content 110.527 medical appointments its 14 associated variables.

Data Dictionary

  1. Patient_Id: Identification of a patient.
  2. Appointment_ID: Identification of each appointment.
  3. Gender: Male or Female, Female is the greater proportion, woman takes way more care of they health in comparison to man.
  4. DataMarcacaoConsulta: The day of the actuall appointment, when they have to visit the doctor.
  5. DataAgendamento: The day someone called or registered the appointment, this is before appointment of course.
  6. Age: How old is the patient.
  7. Neighbourhood: Where the appointment takes place.
  8. Scholarship: True or False.
  9. Hipertension: True or False.
  10. Diabetes: True or False.
  11. Alcoholism: True or False.
  12. Handcap: True or False.
  13. SMS_received: 1 or more messages sent to the patient.
  14. No-show: True or False.

Questions¶

  • The main question we are trying to answer here is why 30% of patients miss their scheduled appointment.

1. Univariate Exploration

  • Q1: What is the percentage of patients who show vs. who don't show?
  • Q2: What percentage of patients are male and female and which one is more booked than the other?
  • Q3: What is waiting days for Scheduled Day?
  • Q4: Which the most booking Ages?
  • Q5: In which Neighborhood are the most appointments taken?
  • Q6: What percentage of patients are Scholarship, Hipertension, Diabetes, Alcoholism, Handcap and SMS_received

2. Bivariate Exploration

  • Q1: What is the percentage of male and female patients who are already attending and who do not attend after booking?
  • Q2: What is the relationship between waiting days and Show the patient?
  • Q3: What is the most mandatory age to actually attend the booking?
  • Q4: What is the five most mandatory neighborhood to attend booking already?
  • Q5: What percentage of patients are Scholarship, Hipertension, Diabetes, Alcoholism, Handcap and SMS_received, And they have already made the booking?

3. Multivariate Exploration

  • Q1: The Distribution of Age For 'Male, Female' and 'Show, Not Show'.
  • Q2: Patients who received SMS compared to those who received SMS and showed up in 8 most booked neighborhoods

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

After Cleaning We have dataset content 110.521 medical appointments its 14 associated variables.

  • 2 Categorical variable(Object).
  • 10 Numeric variable (Integer).
  • 2 Date Time variable.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in one if the patient show-up or no-show to the appointment in the dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think I have advantages in the dataset, which are several specifications for each patient, such as (scholarship, high blood pressure, diabetes, alcohol, hand) as well as appointments (exact day, appointment day).

And This will help me connect the relationships between some of them and find out why not Attending the patient to the doctor

Out[31]:
(0.7981017182254956, 0.2018982817745044)
In [32]:
#define data
data = [show, no_show]
labels = ["Show", "Didn't Show"]
explode = (0, 0.1);
#define Seaborn color palette to use
#colors = sns.color_palette('bright')[0:2]

#create pie chart
plt.pie(data, radius=1.2, explode=explode, labels = labels, autopct='%0.2f%%', textprops = {"fontsize":15});
plt.title("Percentage of patients who showed and who didn't Show",fontsize = 15, fontweight='bold', y=1.2);

Discuss the distribution of variables of interest?¶

  • Show Column

    The Show column depends on it to connect the relationships with each other.

  • Gender Column

    Females are more numerous than males for reservation.

Conclusions¶

Result¶

  • Percentage of patients who Don't show for their appointments = 20.19%
  • The proportion of female patients who book appointments = 65.00%, of them 20% do not Show.
  • The proportion of male patients who book appointments = 35.00% of them 20% do not Show.
  • Most of the actual appointments to visit the doctor are within 0-3 days of booking, And there is no specific relationship to attendance and does not depend on waiting days.
  • 75% of patients who book is 55 years.
  • Older patients (45-old) keep their appointments more often than younger patients (18-35).
  • Most of the five neighborhoods are booked, in order: JARDIM CAMBURI, MARIA ORTIZ, RESISTNCIA, JARDIM DA PENHA, ITARAR.
  • The most mandatory neighborhood to attend reservation is JARDIM DA PENHA.
  • Percentage of patients who have scholarships = 9.83%, them 25% do not Show.
  • percentage of patients who Hypertension = 19.73%, them 18% do not Show.
  • percentage of patients who Diabetes = 7.19%, them 18% do not Show.
  • percentage of patients who Alcoholism = 3.04%, them 20% do not Show.
  • percentage of patients who Handcap = 1.85%, them 18% do not Show.
  • percentage of patients who SMS received = 32.10%, them 30% do not Show.
  • percentage of patients who Not SMS received = 67.90%, them 17% do not Show.
  • The average male patients showing are slightly bigger than women for age.
  • The Show Up Percentage does not depend on sending SMS.

Exploratory¶

  • Gender does not affect the percentage of the show up, there is no difference between males and females.
  • There is no effect or relationship between the delay of days and show up.
  • The older one gets, the more serious the show up.
  • Alcohol affects show up about 20% of those who drink alcohol do not show up.
  • Received SMS affects the show up, about 30% of those who received SMS do not show up.
